WEBVTT

00:15.102 --> 00:17.887
- My name is Alex Horn.
I am 26 years old.

00:18.018 --> 00:20.585
I am super excited
to test myself

00:20.716 --> 00:23.066
and see what
this competition does.

00:23.197 --> 00:25.199
I love challenging myself and
always trying something new,

00:25.329 --> 00:27.244
and just pushing
my skill level.

00:27.375 --> 00:32.032
In the right moment,
I'll blossom and shine.

00:32.162 --> 00:35.992
- My name is Kevin Burkman.
I'm 49 years old.

00:36.123 --> 00:38.299
I retired from the Army
after 24 years.

00:38.429 --> 00:40.953
My first knife that I got
when I was in the military,

00:41.084 --> 00:42.520
I didn't like it,

00:42.651 --> 00:45.132
it didn't fit the gear
that I had, so I made my own.

00:45.262 --> 00:47.873
And then I just
started from there.

00:48.004 --> 00:49.919
- My name is Pat Biggin and
I'm from Elkhorn, Wisconsin.

00:50.050 --> 00:52.356
I started bladesmithing
when my grandpa gave me a knife

00:52.487 --> 00:55.011
that his dad made for him
during the second world war.

00:55.142 --> 00:56.708
And I started
getting interested

00:56.839 --> 00:59.320
in how the process was done,
can I still repeat it.

00:59.450 --> 01:01.713
It's just kind of a way
to pay homage

01:01.844 --> 01:04.107
to my great grandfather's
work skill set

01:04.238 --> 01:05.935
and maintain the tradition
through my family.

01:06.066 --> 01:08.677
- My name is Mike Benton.
I'm 45 years old.

01:08.807 --> 01:10.113
I have a huge family.
I have six kids.

01:10.244 --> 01:12.289
Four girls and two boys.

01:12.420 --> 01:14.770
So, being here,
this is definitely a vacation.

01:14.900 --> 01:16.815
Yeah, yeah, my wife
actually wanted to come.

01:16.946 --> 01:19.253
But my family
is number one to me.

01:19.383 --> 01:20.602
I love my kids,
I love my wife.

01:20.732 --> 01:21.994
I mean, they're the reason

01:22.125 --> 01:24.388
why I work so much
every single day.

01:24.519 --> 01:27.522
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:27.652 --> 01:29.654
Each of you is here
to engage in three rounds

01:29.785 --> 01:31.787
of timed edged weapon
making competitions

01:31.917 --> 01:34.485
specifically designed to test
every aspect of your skills

01:34.616 --> 01:37.097
in front of a panel of expert
judges that will tell us

01:37.227 --> 01:39.577
which of you is the next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:39.708 --> 01:42.319
leaving here with
a check for $10,000.

01:42.450 --> 01:44.930
Let's go ahead
and meet those judges now.

01:45.061 --> 01:47.237
Up first, two-time
Forged in Fire champion,

01:47.368 --> 01:48.717
Ben Abbot.

01:48.847 --> 01:50.936
Next, historic weapons
re-creation specialist,

01:51.067 --> 01:52.112
David Baker.

01:52.242 --> 01:53.765
And last,
edged weapons specialist,

01:53.896 --> 01:55.071
Doug Marcaida.

01:55.202 --> 01:57.073
Bladesmiths,
today's competition

01:57.204 --> 01:59.119
revolves around barbarians,

01:59.249 --> 02:03.079
specifically, the Goths
who sacked Rome in 410 A.D.

02:03.210 --> 02:04.907
Now, along the way,

02:05.037 --> 02:07.388
the Goths seized weapons
of their adversaries

02:07.518 --> 02:09.955
and incorporated them
into their own arsenals,

02:10.086 --> 02:11.870
and today we're going
to ask you to incorporate

02:12.001 --> 02:14.786
these weapons into a billet

02:14.917 --> 02:17.224
from which you will forge
one of these,

02:17.354 --> 02:19.226
a favorite of backstabbers
everywhere.

02:22.533 --> 02:25.623
A pugio dagger.

02:25.754 --> 02:28.539
It is believed that
the pugio was the weapon used

02:28.670 --> 02:30.498
by the senate conspirators
to assassinate

02:30.628 --> 02:34.806
Julius Caesar on the Ides
of March in 44 A.D.

02:34.937 --> 02:37.113
Your challenge here
in the first round

02:37.244 --> 02:39.811
is to use a Hada technique
to combine three or more

02:39.942 --> 02:42.162
of these weapons
to forge a pugio

02:42.292 --> 02:44.207
that falls within
the following parameters.

02:44.338 --> 02:45.948
The length of your blade
must be between eight

02:46.078 --> 02:47.384
and ten inches.

02:47.515 --> 02:49.430
It must have a wasp waist

02:49.560 --> 02:52.084
and be at least
two inches wide at the base.

02:52.215 --> 02:54.130
- I know nothing
about barbarians

02:54.261 --> 02:56.350
and a very little bit
about daggers.

02:56.480 --> 02:57.960
I've never made
a dagger before.

02:58.090 --> 03:00.571
So I'm getting
a little nervous.

03:00.702 --> 03:02.530
- You will have just
three hours

03:02.660 --> 03:04.532
in this first round in which
to complete your work.

03:04.662 --> 03:06.186
If you make it
to the second round,

03:06.316 --> 03:09.014
you will have a chance
to put a handle on your pugio,

03:09.145 --> 03:11.365
making it fully functional
so that we can test it

03:11.495 --> 03:15.586
for strength and durability
in a shield chop and stab,

03:15.717 --> 03:18.154
and for edge retention
in rope slice.

03:18.285 --> 03:20.461
Bladesmiths,
pay attention to the details.

03:20.591 --> 03:22.637
Failure to meet a single one
of our parameters

03:22.767 --> 03:24.334
is grounds
for immediate dismissal

03:24.465 --> 03:26.684
from this forge
with no deliberation.

03:26.815 --> 03:29.774
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

03:32.386 --> 03:35.171
- All right, so these guys
have to combine those steels

03:35.302 --> 03:37.869
into a Hada Damascus billet.

03:38.000 --> 03:40.655
Hada technique
is really just layering

03:40.785 --> 03:42.526
of the same types
of steel, right?

03:42.657 --> 03:46.487
- It's a really ancient
technique of using up scraps.

03:46.617 --> 03:50.665
- We've got our smiths kind
of disassembling some knives.

03:50.795 --> 03:52.884
Why aren't these guys
just cutting off, like,

03:53.015 --> 03:55.800
shafts and blades
and stacking that stuff up?

03:55.931 --> 03:57.802
- Because it's more fun
hitting things with hammers.

03:57.933 --> 03:58.934
- Yeah.

03:59.064 --> 04:00.196
- Pros of the Hada technique

04:00.327 --> 04:02.198
is it's all the same type
of steel.

04:02.329 --> 04:04.809
The downside is that
I then have to make sure

04:04.940 --> 04:06.594
I have enough steel
in my starting billet

04:06.724 --> 04:08.726
to be able to get that
parameter for length and width.

04:08.857 --> 04:10.728
I am thinking,
which are the flattest?

04:10.859 --> 04:13.209
Which are the most similar
is size already?

04:13.340 --> 04:15.429
Get rid of all
the scale rust,

04:15.559 --> 04:18.127
any type of garbage
that will inhibit a weld.

04:18.258 --> 04:19.955
- There's plenty
of steel out there

04:20.085 --> 04:22.653
for any of these guys to make
an eight- to ten-inch blade.

04:22.784 --> 04:23.915
- But, they're short,
fat blades.

04:24.046 --> 04:25.569
They're gonna have to make
a good stack

04:25.700 --> 04:27.876
so they can pour it out
wide enough.

04:28.006 --> 04:29.704
A base of this blade
is about two inches,

04:29.834 --> 04:31.271
two and a quarter inches wide.

04:31.401 --> 04:32.489
- The challenging thing
with daggers

04:32.620 --> 04:33.925
is getting them symmetric

04:34.056 --> 04:36.667
and all four faces
of the bevel to be even.

04:36.798 --> 04:38.713
That's something
I've basically struggled with

04:38.843 --> 04:40.236
when I started making them,

04:40.367 --> 04:42.020
and it's kind of why
I stopped making them.

04:42.151 --> 04:44.762
- One of the things that's hard
when you start doing daggers

04:44.893 --> 04:47.722
or symmetrical shapes is
actually finding that symmetry.

04:47.852 --> 04:50.072
A dagger profile
is difficult

04:50.202 --> 04:51.943
and different
from a traditional knife,

04:52.074 --> 04:54.685
in that you have to shape four
identical sides instead of two

04:54.816 --> 04:58.167
to get that traditional
diamond shape of the dagger.

04:58.298 --> 04:59.647
- I've made daggers before,

04:59.777 --> 05:02.824
but this pugo
or pahuahua thing,

05:02.954 --> 05:06.654
it's wide, its longer
than I normally make.

05:06.784 --> 05:09.134
But you know what, I've never
run away from a challenge.

05:09.265 --> 05:10.832
So let's tear it up.

05:10.962 --> 05:13.269
For my stack I want
to have nine pieces, or more,

05:13.400 --> 05:15.706
so that way when you do
draw this out,

05:15.837 --> 05:17.621
you want to have more metal
than you need.

05:17.752 --> 05:19.971
Having more is better
than not having enough.

05:20.102 --> 05:21.799
- When you stack a billet,

05:21.930 --> 05:24.149
you want to make sure
all of them are the same size.

05:24.280 --> 05:26.891
If there's any that stick out
bigger than the other,

05:27.022 --> 05:28.719
you'll get,
right at the edge there,

05:28.850 --> 05:31.113
you'll get this cold shut
where it rolls over eventually,

05:31.243 --> 05:33.289
and it doesn't make
a good weld.

05:33.420 --> 05:34.899
- I am goal oriented.

05:35.030 --> 05:37.075
Goal one is to make it
to round two.

05:37.206 --> 05:39.687
Goal two is to get
to round three.

05:39.817 --> 05:42.167
Goal three is to be
"Forged in Fire" champion.

05:42.298 --> 05:44.039
- I want to make
this billet setup

05:44.169 --> 05:45.170
as easy as it can be.

05:45.301 --> 05:47.782
So I grab the straightest,

05:47.912 --> 05:50.393
most square
looking weapons that I see.

05:50.524 --> 05:52.569
I grab four of them just to
make sure I have enough steel.

05:52.700 --> 05:54.484
My mind's going
a mile a minute.

05:54.615 --> 05:56.007
I've never made
a dagger before,

05:56.138 --> 05:57.531
and I just got to get
the jitters out,

05:57.661 --> 05:59.359
get in my groove,

05:59.489 --> 06:02.971
just making another billet
like I do every day.

06:03.101 --> 06:05.365
Right now,
I've got my billet welded up.

06:05.495 --> 06:06.714
I've got six separate pieces,

06:06.844 --> 06:08.977
about four inches
by an inch wide,

06:09.107 --> 06:10.631
got it tacked up,
heating up.

06:10.761 --> 06:12.807
I've still got a few jitters
that I got to work out,

06:12.937 --> 06:14.374
but I think once

06:14.504 --> 06:17.681
I've got my billet set,
I'm going to be rolling.

06:17.812 --> 06:19.161
- Double edged daggers,
I have no problem with.

06:19.291 --> 06:20.815
I've made them.

06:20.945 --> 06:22.773
But the challenge
with this weapon

06:22.904 --> 06:24.427
is the weapon
has to be symmetrical,

06:24.558 --> 06:25.950
and you can't be off.

06:26.081 --> 06:27.735
The judges will see that,
they will know that.

06:27.865 --> 06:29.867
If your measurement's wrong,
you can go home.

06:29.998 --> 06:32.000
If you don't do your welds
right, you can go home.

06:32.130 --> 06:35.525
I don't want to go home.
I want to be number one.

06:35.656 --> 06:38.528
- One of the things I love
about challenges like this

06:38.659 --> 06:40.443
is there's plenty
of steel out there,

06:40.574 --> 06:41.749
it's just not
in the right shape.

06:41.879 --> 06:43.228
- Yeah.

06:43.359 --> 06:45.448
- And it's up to them
to take those shapes,

06:45.579 --> 06:48.146
forge all of them together,
and make a new shape,

06:48.277 --> 06:51.715
and that material management,
that planning, is everything.

06:51.846 --> 06:53.238
- Yeah.

06:53.369 --> 06:56.111
- I hand-hammer
to set the welds.

06:56.241 --> 06:59.854
I prefer to do it by hand
because I know I'm swinging it

06:59.984 --> 07:02.465
at the right weight,
the right speed.

07:02.596 --> 07:04.946
- Kevin, he did start
with a nice, uniform stack.

07:05.076 --> 07:07.644
But it looked to me
like an inch and a half cube,

07:07.775 --> 07:10.560
a little bit lean on the amount
of material for this knife.

07:10.691 --> 07:13.563
- When I know
my forge welds are set,

07:13.694 --> 07:16.087
I start drawing the billet
out length wise.

07:16.218 --> 07:19.439
I don't want to push out
too much metal at one time.

07:19.569 --> 07:21.702
I want to maintain
that thickness of the blade

07:21.832 --> 07:24.748
because I know the judges
are brutal when they test.

07:24.879 --> 07:27.098
Hot metal!

07:27.229 --> 07:29.405
, I don't know
if I got enough material.

07:32.582 --> 07:33.757
- Every time you forge weld,

07:33.888 --> 07:35.542
there's always
a chance of failure.

07:35.672 --> 07:38.240
So every time I forge weld,
I'm nervous.

07:38.370 --> 07:40.895
My first forge weld
is just a nice,

07:41.025 --> 07:43.027
light tap to make sure
everything is set.

07:43.158 --> 07:44.942
Then once I know
that weld is set,

07:45.073 --> 07:47.815
I can start drawing
this billet out.

07:47.945 --> 07:50.121
In this competition I think
I have a good advantage

07:50.252 --> 07:52.472
in that, you know,
I'm pretty adept at forging.

07:52.602 --> 07:53.864
I've forged probably close
to 1,000 knives now

07:53.995 --> 07:55.649
in the past three years.

07:55.779 --> 07:58.260
But you can never stop
learning about knives,

07:58.390 --> 08:00.610
and I want to learn
until the day I die

08:00.741 --> 08:02.873
and make the best knife
I can possibly make every day.

08:07.878 --> 08:10.054
- When you're forge welding,
it's a repetitive process.

08:10.185 --> 08:13.231
You have to heat,
hammer, heat, hammer.

08:13.362 --> 08:15.625
So it becomes one solid
piece of metal.

08:15.756 --> 08:17.366
And when you're
forge welding,

08:17.497 --> 08:20.456
its hit it as hard as you can,
as fast as you can.

08:20.587 --> 08:22.284
- When you come out
of the forge

08:22.414 --> 08:26.070
and you can see different
colorations in even stacks,

08:26.201 --> 08:27.942
I mean, you know
that they're not connected,

08:28.072 --> 08:29.247
it's not a good weld.
- Yeah.

08:29.378 --> 08:30.901
- Once I get this forged
and set,

08:31.032 --> 08:32.729
then I'll take it to big blue.

08:32.860 --> 08:34.601
The thing I'm most worried
about is my welds not taking.

08:34.731 --> 08:36.559
Because if those welds don't
take, you don't have a billet.

08:36.690 --> 08:39.257
You don't have a billet,
you don't have a knife.

08:41.259 --> 08:42.522
- Looking on the inside
of the bar,

08:42.652 --> 08:44.001
it looks like
it's pretty good.

08:44.132 --> 08:46.743
There's no cracks I can see,
there's no delams.

08:46.874 --> 08:48.963
It looks like it's
a nice clean, solid weld.

08:49.093 --> 08:52.183
- Pat's billet looks
a little bit undersized

08:52.314 --> 08:54.403
when we talk about that
eight- to ten-inch blade.

08:54.534 --> 08:56.710
- Yeah.
- Plus tang.

08:56.840 --> 08:58.755
- Ultimate end for the steel,
I'm looking for something

08:58.886 --> 09:00.931
that is a little bit longer

09:01.062 --> 09:03.281
than the parameters
in the initial body.

09:03.412 --> 09:05.022
I can then put
any extra material

09:05.153 --> 09:06.676
that becomes a little bit
too large for me

09:06.807 --> 09:08.112
to deal with for the blade
into the tang,

09:08.243 --> 09:09.549
and it can be removed later.

09:09.679 --> 09:12.334
- Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed.

09:12.464 --> 09:16.294
You have just two hours
remaining to finish your work.

09:16.425 --> 09:18.079
- Whoo!

09:23.258 --> 09:25.434
- There goes Mike,
working it cold again.

09:25.565 --> 09:27.044
I mean, it's all red.

09:27.175 --> 09:29.003
- I think my forge welds
are good.

09:29.133 --> 09:31.614
So now I need
to lengthen my steel.

09:31.745 --> 09:33.660
- I think that we're gonna see

09:33.790 --> 09:35.183
some serious problems
with those welds.

09:37.141 --> 09:39.230
- But I actually make
are good.e - I thins

09:39.361 --> 09:40.710
I turn it on the side...

09:40.841 --> 09:42.669
And it starts to split apart,

09:42.799 --> 09:44.584
and that's not
what you want to see.

09:44.714 --> 09:47.891
- When Mike set his first weld,
it was really cold.

09:48.022 --> 09:49.850
I mean, it was a dull red,
and you really want

09:49.980 --> 09:51.634
a bright whit heat.
- Right.

09:51.765 --> 09:56.073
- I'm wasting time having
to re-set the forge welds.

09:56.204 --> 09:57.771
That's something
you can't afford to do

09:57.901 --> 09:59.555
in a three-hour build.

10:03.690 --> 10:05.822
- We are almost 90 minutes

10:05.953 --> 10:08.303
into this first round
of competition,

10:08.433 --> 10:11.567
and I see a lot of shapes.

10:11.698 --> 10:13.874
I don't see any pugio shapes
out there yet.

10:14.004 --> 10:16.224
- Here's the thing,
the pugio exists

10:16.354 --> 10:19.836
in the Roman Empire
for 600, 700 years.

10:19.967 --> 10:21.621
So there are
a lot of variations.

10:21.751 --> 10:23.753
That wasp waist
is on all of them,

10:23.884 --> 10:27.061
but the head tends
to vary a bit.

10:28.758 --> 10:30.455
- I've got the steel
drawn out to a long,

10:30.586 --> 10:32.632
tapered, pointy object.

10:32.762 --> 10:34.416
I've got it thick enough that
I should be able hand widen

10:34.546 --> 10:36.070
that blade out
to where I need it.

10:36.200 --> 10:38.725
- Pat's blade.
Are you guys seeing a pugio?

10:38.855 --> 10:40.291
- I'm not.

10:40.422 --> 10:44.208
- The very long tip
from that wasp waist.

10:44.339 --> 10:46.210
- It's a very tall wasp.
- Yeah.

10:46.341 --> 10:50.301
- Width wise,
a little shy on that.

10:50.432 --> 10:52.564
I'm actually
a quarter inch under.

10:52.695 --> 10:54.218
At this point
I'd have to add steel

10:54.349 --> 10:55.698
to get more width
to the blade,

10:55.829 --> 10:58.005
and I don't think
I would have enough time.

10:58.135 --> 11:00.660
I'm just gonna continue on with
what I'm doing and squeeze out

11:00.790 --> 11:02.357
enough material
on both sides

11:02.487 --> 11:05.795
to make up the difference,
and I should be good to go.

11:05.926 --> 11:08.189
- It's looking great.

11:08.319 --> 11:11.235
I'm trying to shape as much
as I can with my hammer.

11:11.366 --> 11:12.672
My shape's
coming along nicely.

11:12.802 --> 11:14.674
I'm starting to see
that pugio-looking thing.

11:14.804 --> 11:16.632
I get the hips into it,

11:16.763 --> 11:19.461
but I don't have
enough metal for the tang.

11:19.591 --> 11:21.289
I got this piece
from one of my weapons

11:21.419 --> 11:23.030
and I'm gonna weld this
on as my tang.

11:23.160 --> 11:25.032
Hot, hot.
Son of a--

11:25.162 --> 11:26.686
- Kevin--
- There you go.

11:26.816 --> 11:29.123
- I think Kevin
grabbed some more steel.

11:29.253 --> 11:30.602
- Ah, got me.

11:30.733 --> 11:32.169
- Kevin made a blade shape,

11:32.300 --> 11:35.738
and then welded a tang
right at the junction

11:35.869 --> 11:39.742
between tang and blade,
and that's a weak spot.

11:39.873 --> 11:41.526
- Right, it's the junction
between the business end

11:41.657 --> 11:43.615
and the user end.
- Yeah.

11:43.746 --> 11:45.356
- Welding a tang onto
this knife

11:45.487 --> 11:47.097
will create a weak spot,

11:47.228 --> 11:48.708
but it's going
to meet the parameters.

11:48.838 --> 11:50.361
And, if I make it
to round two,

11:50.492 --> 11:52.755
I'll figure out how to
reinforce that weak spot.

11:52.886 --> 11:55.715
- I'm watching Alex right now
use the horn of the anvil

11:55.845 --> 11:57.629
and a hammer
to create that wasp waist.

11:57.760 --> 11:59.501
- Yeah.

11:59.631 --> 12:01.764
- So right now, I just
finished forging my blade.

12:01.895 --> 12:02.983
Next, I'm going to get
the profile

12:03.113 --> 12:04.767
of the knife on the grinder,

12:04.898 --> 12:07.378
maybe add a little bit of
beveling before heat treat.

12:07.509 --> 12:09.380
But I did a lot of it
with the forging,

12:09.511 --> 12:11.382
so I shouldn't have too much
to do on grinding.

12:11.513 --> 12:14.081
- His profile is spot on.

12:14.211 --> 12:16.039
- It's feeling really good,
it's got a nice weight to it.

12:16.170 --> 12:17.998
I think it should do
really good in the chop test.

12:18.128 --> 12:19.956
Plenty of strength
in the tip for a stab.

12:20.087 --> 12:21.871
So I'm feeling all right.

12:25.483 --> 12:27.790
- I don't know
the quality of his welds,

12:27.921 --> 12:30.488
but Mike has really been able
to draw that metal out,

12:30.619 --> 12:32.447
and he's got
a great pugio shape.

12:32.577 --> 12:34.318
- Yeah.
- Okay.

12:34.449 --> 12:36.059
- My blade's
coming together great.

12:36.190 --> 12:37.757
I think that my point
isn't quite as drastic

12:37.887 --> 12:39.628
as some of my competitors,

12:39.759 --> 12:42.544
but I think that mine
looks more like the example.

12:42.674 --> 12:45.895
It's ugly, but it's good.

12:46.026 --> 12:47.723
- Bladesmiths!

12:47.854 --> 12:50.465
30 minutes remaining
in the round.

12:50.595 --> 12:52.946
- I see that my tang is
delaminating at the very end,

12:53.076 --> 12:54.861
but I think I have
enough steel to cut off

12:54.991 --> 12:57.733
that delaminated
part of the tang.

12:57.864 --> 12:59.779
So my knife's finally ready
for heat treat,

12:59.909 --> 13:03.565
and the one thing I do not want
to do is overheat this steel.

13:03.695 --> 13:05.045
I just spent so much time
forging it.

13:05.175 --> 13:08.048
I want to quench this
as perfectly as I can.

13:08.178 --> 13:09.832
So I'm just moving it back
and forth to try

13:09.963 --> 13:13.357
and even this heat out.

13:13.488 --> 13:17.144
- Alex did manage to do
a period-correct Caesar quench.

13:17.274 --> 13:18.798
- Caesar quench?
- Yes.

13:18.928 --> 13:21.496
He stabbed that forge 23 times,
moving it in and out,

13:21.626 --> 13:23.280
before he went to the oil.

13:23.411 --> 13:25.326
- My knife's looking
pretty straight.

13:25.456 --> 13:28.111
It sounds hard, it looks hard.
I'm feeling good.

13:29.591 --> 13:31.288
- Well, this is what
I've got so far.

13:31.419 --> 13:33.073
I've got to go into
the heat treat

13:33.203 --> 13:36.728
and then do a little
more finish grinding.

13:36.859 --> 13:39.470
- Kevin just
quenched his blade.

13:39.601 --> 13:41.211
- He's file-testing it.

13:41.342 --> 13:43.039
- Yeah.
- That was quick.

13:43.170 --> 13:44.649
- That was very fast.

13:44.780 --> 13:47.609
- You've got to be
kidding me.

13:47.739 --> 13:49.785
Half of it's heat treated,
half of it's not.

13:49.916 --> 13:52.092
That is bad news.

13:52.222 --> 13:55.443
On the second heat treat,
I bring it up to cherry red,

13:55.573 --> 13:57.271
and I got the same
problem again.

13:57.401 --> 14:00.404
- Kevin may be file checking
while it's still hot

14:00.535 --> 14:01.797
and thinking
it didn't get hard.

14:01.928 --> 14:03.886
So going for another quench,
and then another quench.

14:04.017 --> 14:06.062
- Oh, that makes sense.

14:06.193 --> 14:07.977
- I'm starting to feel
the pressure.

14:08.108 --> 14:09.936
I know I got to get
on that grinder

14:10.066 --> 14:11.894
to start getting
this thing cleaned up.

14:12.025 --> 14:13.591
- The tip looks very hot.
- Yeah.

14:13.722 --> 14:15.158
- Come on, dude.

14:18.553 --> 14:20.424
- Nope.
What the hell's going on?

14:20.555 --> 14:21.643
I don't know what I'm
doing wrong here.

14:27.649 --> 14:29.433
Oh, she's hard now.

14:29.564 --> 14:32.132
Whew.
I'm good. I'm good.

14:33.916 --> 14:36.963
- Looks like Pat's gonna start
his heat-treat process.

14:37.093 --> 14:38.660
- Yeah, he's got it in
tang first,

14:38.790 --> 14:40.314
so he's not
overheating the tip.

14:40.444 --> 14:41.837
That's good.

14:45.232 --> 14:46.886
- Looks good and straight.

14:47.016 --> 14:50.324
I'm gonna take it over to the
grinder, finish up my profile.

14:50.454 --> 14:52.935
- I don't know how
Pat's going to a grinder.

14:53.066 --> 14:56.634
You can't grind metal
onto a blade.

14:56.765 --> 14:59.115
- A very subtle wasp waist.

14:59.246 --> 15:01.291
- Like he's making
a metal Christmas tree.

15:04.294 --> 15:07.471
- The heat treat/the quench
is what hardens your blade

15:07.602 --> 15:10.866
so that when you do chopping or
cutting, it'll keep its edge.

15:10.997 --> 15:13.347
So I need it to be
fully hardened.

15:15.001 --> 15:18.439
Perfect.

15:18.569 --> 15:20.745
- Mike's really bringing it
home with his shape, I think.

15:20.876 --> 15:22.660
- Yeah.

15:27.839 --> 15:29.015
-Ten seconds!

15:29.145 --> 15:30.581
- Yeah.
- Not pretty but--

15:30.712 --> 15:32.192
- It'll work.

15:32.322 --> 15:37.414
-Five, four, three, two, one.

15:37.545 --> 15:39.025
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

15:39.155 --> 15:41.549
drop your tools,
stop what you're doing.

15:41.679 --> 15:44.073
This first round of
bladesmithing competition

15:44.204 --> 15:45.988
is over.

15:46.119 --> 15:47.076
- Yeah, boys.

15:47.207 --> 15:48.860
- Whoo!

15:51.863 --> 15:53.082
- I feel good about
turning my blade in

15:53.213 --> 15:54.214
looking the way it does.

15:54.344 --> 15:56.172
I feel like
I've hit the parameters.

15:56.303 --> 15:59.610
I have a good working knife.

15:59.741 --> 16:00.960
- All right, bladesmiths,

16:01.090 --> 16:02.570
in this first round
of competition,

16:02.700 --> 16:05.007
we asked you
to produce a pugio

16:05.138 --> 16:06.661
between eight and ten
inches in length.

16:06.791 --> 16:07.967
Now, the judges want to see

16:08.097 --> 16:09.664
what you've done
with yourselves.

16:09.794 --> 16:10.970
Mike, you're up first.

16:11.100 --> 16:13.885
Please present your pugio
to the judges.

16:17.150 --> 16:20.022
- Well, Mike, the profile
is pretty Pugi-esque.

16:20.153 --> 16:22.198
There is a wasp waist here.

16:22.329 --> 16:25.549
There is a nice flair,
front and back.

16:25.680 --> 16:28.509
Yeah, it's
a good-looking blade.

16:28.639 --> 16:29.901
- All right Kevin,
you're up.

16:30.032 --> 16:32.078
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:33.818 --> 16:35.429
- I like the fact
you've got the waist here,

16:35.559 --> 16:37.387
I like the fact you've got
the pronounced shoulders here.

16:37.518 --> 16:38.954
You know,
that tip meandering over,

16:39.085 --> 16:42.610
that's hard to get my eyes
around that hard lean.

16:42.740 --> 16:46.918
Where you did weld
on this added tang,

16:47.049 --> 16:51.053
I can see
the top edge of that weld.

16:51.184 --> 16:53.882
You've kind of built
in a questionable spot.

16:54.013 --> 16:56.667
So I would do everything
you can to reinforce that area

16:56.798 --> 16:58.756
if you move forward.

16:58.887 --> 17:00.584
- Roger that.
- Alex, you're up next.

17:00.715 --> 17:03.587
Please present your blade
to the judges.

17:05.807 --> 17:08.984
- Well, Alex, this is
a really good pugio shape.

17:09.115 --> 17:11.465
You captured the essence
of the knife very well.

17:11.595 --> 17:13.119
The only thing that
gives me pause

17:13.249 --> 17:16.992
is that there's
not a lot of tang here.

17:17.123 --> 17:18.733
It's right to the end
of my hand.

17:18.863 --> 17:20.822
So, if you're gonna put pommel
on it, or anything like that,

17:20.952 --> 17:23.303
it's gonna need
to be extended somehow,

17:23.433 --> 17:25.609
but, other than that,
well done.

17:25.740 --> 17:26.784
- Thank you.

17:26.915 --> 17:28.525
- Pat...

17:28.656 --> 17:31.354
unfortunately the judges
won't be evaluating your work

17:31.485 --> 17:33.835
because your blade failed
to meet parameters.

17:35.793 --> 17:37.708
It is an inch and
seven-eighths at the base

17:37.839 --> 17:40.059
and falls short of our
two-inch minimum requirement.

17:40.189 --> 17:41.712
And, for that reason,

17:41.843 --> 17:43.845
I'd like to ask you to please
surrender your blade.

17:45.412 --> 17:47.283
- A little disappointed,

17:47.414 --> 17:49.416
but I gave it the best try
I could for the time I had.

17:49.546 --> 17:52.288
My blade was under parameters
on the shoulders.

17:52.419 --> 17:54.029
I even tried to re-widen it,

17:54.160 --> 17:55.596
and when I was doing
my final grinding,

17:55.726 --> 17:57.119
I must have just taken
a little bit more off the edge

17:57.250 --> 17:58.903
than I really thought.

17:59.034 --> 18:01.036
But I'm planning on making
a pugio when I get home

18:01.167 --> 18:02.733
because it bothers me

18:02.864 --> 18:04.953
that I missed
the mark on daggers,

18:05.084 --> 18:07.825
and now I'm obsessed
with trying to figure out

18:07.956 --> 18:09.218
how to do it the right way.

18:12.003 --> 18:14.049
- Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

18:14.180 --> 18:15.398
You guys have made it

18:15.529 --> 18:16.921
to the second round
of this competition,

18:17.052 --> 18:18.575
and now that those blades
have been tempered,

18:18.706 --> 18:19.968
it's time to make them
fully funconal pugios

18:20.099 --> 18:21.970
by attaching handles to them

18:22.101 --> 18:24.886
and correcting the deficiencies
from the first round.

18:25.016 --> 18:26.583
In addition to a handle,

18:26.714 --> 18:28.281
you must have a medallion
in the handle,

18:28.411 --> 18:31.022
you must have a guard,
and you must have a pommel.

18:31.153 --> 18:33.024
Failure to do so means
immediate dismissal

18:33.155 --> 18:34.591
from this forge
with no deliberation.

18:34.722 --> 18:36.506
You'll have just two hours

18:36.637 --> 18:38.334
in which to complete
all this work.

18:38.465 --> 18:40.858
After this round, your blades
will be tested for strength

18:40.989 --> 18:44.210
and durability
in a shield stab and slice

18:44.340 --> 18:47.343
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

18:47.474 --> 18:49.911
Good luck, bladesmiths,
your two hours starts now.

18:52.522 --> 18:54.916
Okay, so these guys
have just two hours

18:55.046 --> 18:57.136
to attach these handles
with medallions,

18:57.266 --> 18:59.355
with disk pommels
and with guards.

18:59.486 --> 19:01.096
- You know, it's funny,
the medallion

19:01.227 --> 19:02.793
is gonna be the weirdest
little trip up,

19:02.924 --> 19:04.621
'cause it's either
gonna be really easy,

19:04.752 --> 19:05.927
you make one out of sheet,

19:06.057 --> 19:07.276
you stick it on either side
and you're done;

19:07.407 --> 19:09.278
or you make a more solid one
like the example is.

19:09.409 --> 19:11.237
Now you have
some fiddly fitting up

19:11.367 --> 19:13.282
of the handle materials
to get it all to sit up right.

19:13.413 --> 19:15.545
- All right.
- Yeah.

19:15.676 --> 19:18.722
So, I made it
to round two, check.

19:18.853 --> 19:20.507
Now I need to bring the tip

19:20.637 --> 19:22.596
back to the center
of the blade.

19:22.726 --> 19:25.338
If I was gonna take out Caesar
with a crooked blade,

19:25.468 --> 19:27.992
I'd be the embarrassment
of the entire Roman Empire.

19:28.123 --> 19:30.734
So I've got to have
a straight blade.

19:30.865 --> 19:35.130
I'm grinding off
the one edge of the blade

19:35.261 --> 19:38.786
until that tip slowly moves
back to the center.

19:38.916 --> 19:41.267
- I do see a lot
of good sparks in there,

19:41.397 --> 19:43.182
so he's really
grinding in there.

19:43.312 --> 19:46.141
Hopefully just one side
to match the other.

19:46.272 --> 19:48.752
- Oops.

19:50.406 --> 19:52.016
- So I'm feeling okay
about my blade,

19:52.147 --> 19:54.062
but there's so much
handle work to do

19:54.193 --> 19:57.674
that it's just insane
trying to do it in two hours.

19:57.805 --> 20:00.329
First thing I'm doing is
laying out my handle materials

20:00.460 --> 20:02.766
to see how much tang
I need to add on.

20:02.897 --> 20:04.551
- Alex's tang was short,

20:04.681 --> 20:06.596
so he's over there dropping
beads like it's Mardi Gras.

20:10.731 --> 20:12.733
- Alex has taken
a very hot weld

20:12.863 --> 20:14.517
and quenched
that weld in water.

20:14.648 --> 20:15.823
- No!
- Oh, yeah.

20:15.953 --> 20:17.477
- I know not to do that.

20:17.607 --> 20:20.262
- Welding something,
with the heat at that area,

20:20.393 --> 20:22.482
cooling it off with water is
gonna make it hard and brittle,

20:22.612 --> 20:24.919
and they break.

20:25.049 --> 20:26.877
- No, there we go.

20:27.008 --> 20:28.444
I'm so excited
to be in round two.

20:28.575 --> 20:31.055
But, uh, I got
ten hours of work

20:31.186 --> 20:33.144
I got to do in two hours,
I don't know.

20:33.275 --> 20:34.494
There it is.

20:34.624 --> 20:35.886
I need to put a guard on.

20:36.017 --> 20:39.238
I'm going with a thin
piece of brass.

20:39.368 --> 20:41.240
- The guard and the pommel,

20:41.370 --> 20:43.067
should it be made out
of brass or bronze?

20:43.198 --> 20:45.200
- I think brass or bronze
would have been,

20:45.331 --> 20:46.332
uh, would have been correct
for the period.

20:46.462 --> 20:47.724
I would probably
go with that,

20:47.855 --> 20:49.596
and it's easier to file
and fit up.

20:49.726 --> 20:51.250
- All right.

20:51.380 --> 20:52.555
- Not beautiful,
but it works.

20:52.686 --> 20:54.905
- Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed.

20:55.036 --> 20:57.430
You have just one hour
remaining to finish your work.

20:58.953 --> 21:01.825
- Fixing the tip
put me way behind.

21:01.956 --> 21:05.525
The plan is to get
a block of brass

21:05.655 --> 21:08.571
and plunge a hole down
the middle of it

21:08.702 --> 21:11.966
so that the tang can snugly
fit into it to reinforce

21:12.096 --> 21:15.491
that weak weld point
when I welded on the tang.

21:15.622 --> 21:17.711
So close, so close.

21:19.016 --> 21:21.541
Oh, mother of pearl.

21:21.671 --> 21:23.804
I get the guard
somewhat firmly attached,

21:23.934 --> 21:27.242
then I move on to
the medallion and the pommel.

21:27.373 --> 21:30.680
I cut off four pieces
of this brass round stock,

21:30.811 --> 21:32.421
and I'm gonna use two pieces
for my pommel

21:32.552 --> 21:35.032
and two pieces
for my medallion.

21:35.163 --> 21:38.035
Sexy is not what
I'm going for right now.

21:38.166 --> 21:40.168
But then again,
you got this.

21:40.299 --> 21:41.561
- I've got my guard
fitted up,

21:41.691 --> 21:43.606
and I'm gonna start
building this handle.

21:43.737 --> 21:46.479
I need to get a top piece
of wood, the medallion,

21:46.609 --> 21:48.437
bottom piece of wood,
and the pommel fitted up

21:48.568 --> 21:50.091
before I can even glue
and start grinding.

21:52.702 --> 21:54.487
I get these pieces fitted up

21:54.617 --> 21:56.489
and I just really need
to get these holes drilled

21:56.619 --> 21:59.013
so I can pin my medallion,
lock my handle up,

21:59.143 --> 22:01.929
and then get it ground.

22:02.059 --> 22:04.366
- Okay, that not work.

22:04.497 --> 22:06.325
- Is he drilling all of
his layers in one shot or--

22:06.455 --> 22:07.500
- Yeah.

22:07.630 --> 22:09.066
- I can feel the drill bit

22:09.197 --> 22:11.112
start to move
through the steel.

22:11.242 --> 22:12.853
- Alex is working with
some really big drill bits.

22:12.983 --> 22:15.159
Hopefully he hasn't thinned out
his handle material enough

22:15.290 --> 22:16.552
that it's gonna be weak.

22:16.683 --> 22:18.380
- Right.

22:19.076 --> 22:21.383
all: Ohh!

22:22.863 --> 22:24.299
- So I start drilling,

22:24.430 --> 22:27.824
and the tang that
I welded on breaks off.

22:27.955 --> 22:29.652
- 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

22:29.783 --> 22:32.307
- Luckily, my epoxy
hasn't fully cured yet.

22:32.438 --> 22:34.048
So I pull off
that second piece

22:34.178 --> 22:35.658
and rush over to the welder

22:35.789 --> 22:38.139
and try and tack
this tang back on.

22:38.269 --> 22:39.749
- It's unfortunate.

22:39.880 --> 22:41.969
Alex did that final weld
and then quenched it.

22:42.099 --> 22:45.015
You know, that makes
for a really brittle area.

22:45.146 --> 22:47.235
- I'm freaking out
that I'm not actually

22:47.366 --> 22:49.106
going to be able
to finish a knife.

22:51.544 --> 22:53.154
- Are you kidding me?

22:53.284 --> 22:54.677
So as I'm grinding it out,

22:54.808 --> 22:56.723
I find a small hole
in my wood handle.

22:56.853 --> 22:58.028
Look at that.

22:58.159 --> 23:01.075
So I fill it with epoxy.

23:01.205 --> 23:03.207
I'm filling the holes,
I'm covering the handle.

23:03.338 --> 23:06.820
Whatever it is, it is now
an epoxy-handled knife.

23:06.950 --> 23:09.388
- It's dripping
epoxy off of it.

23:09.518 --> 23:11.390
It's, like, oozing
off the of blade.

23:11.520 --> 23:14.218
- But that's just it, you
can't fill a hole with epoxy

23:14.349 --> 23:15.959
and then let it sit sideways.

23:16.090 --> 23:17.613
The epoxy will run out
of the hole.

23:19.528 --> 23:22.096
- These medallions
are killing me.

23:22.226 --> 23:23.924
Time's ticking away.

23:24.054 --> 23:26.405
I still got to throw
a handle onto it.

23:26.535 --> 23:29.582
- Kevin's handle is literally
just the metal pieces.

23:29.712 --> 23:31.758
- I grab some deer leather

23:31.888 --> 23:33.934
and I start
cutting strips of it,

23:34.064 --> 23:35.501
and I just start
slapping glue on it.

23:35.631 --> 23:37.024
Stretching it
and wrapping it,

23:37.154 --> 23:38.852
stretching it
and wrapping it.

23:38.982 --> 23:41.637
- There's a work around,
a leather-wrapped tang.

23:41.768 --> 23:43.683
- Because that is genius.

23:43.813 --> 23:45.380
- That's what he did,
right there.

23:45.511 --> 23:46.599
- I love it.

23:46.729 --> 23:48.557
- Get an edge
on this real fast.

23:48.688 --> 23:50.298
I got five minutes
for the glue to set up,

23:50.429 --> 23:52.300
so I start getting
on the grinder

23:52.431 --> 23:54.911
to put an edge
on this thing.

23:55.042 --> 23:57.914
- Did Mike put any medallions
on his handle yet?

23:58.045 --> 24:00.439
- I don't know.

24:00.569 --> 24:01.701
- I need to attach
my medallions.

24:01.831 --> 24:03.354
Agh!

24:03.485 --> 24:06.140
I can do this with
a larger piece of brass

24:06.270 --> 24:08.751
that I used for the pommel.

24:08.882 --> 24:11.580
As I try and cut it,
it doesn't work out.

24:11.711 --> 24:14.061
I have to scrap the idea
and do something else.

24:14.191 --> 24:15.497
Let's do it.

24:15.628 --> 24:17.891
I don't have time to make it
a perfect replica.

24:18.021 --> 24:19.893
I'm doing what I have to
to make it a functional knife

24:20.023 --> 24:21.721
that represents what they want.

24:23.418 --> 24:25.681
I find some really
big pin stock.

24:25.812 --> 24:28.379
It'll be a smaller medallion.

24:28.510 --> 24:30.686
- The normal construction
with the medallion,

24:30.817 --> 24:32.558
sliding it over...
- Okay.

24:32.688 --> 24:35.386
- So there's a round medallion
in the middle, just like this.

24:35.517 --> 24:38.433
- Okay.
- Or you can do a two-piece

24:38.564 --> 24:40.522
construction like this,
sandwich it.

24:40.653 --> 24:43.612
As long as visually
that medallion exists

24:43.743 --> 24:45.266
as the palm slot.
- Yeah.

24:45.396 --> 24:47.921
- It's just a matter
of sizing that properly.

24:49.575 --> 24:52.708
- Five minutes bladesmiths!

24:52.839 --> 24:55.581
Alex set himself back
with this crappy weld

24:55.711 --> 24:57.278
that he dipped into water.

24:57.408 --> 25:00.063
His tang snapped off,
he's had to re-weld it back on.

25:00.194 --> 25:02.022
Now he's scrambling

25:02.152 --> 25:04.546
and you can see that
he's a little bit flustered.

25:04.677 --> 25:06.766
- I don't even know
what to focus on.

25:06.896 --> 25:08.985
I've got to get
this handle shaped down

25:09.116 --> 25:11.597
to at least
